<h1>Rig Count Stays Strong Across The Basin</h1>

<p>Rig activity remains strong across the Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin --
it is the seventh straight week that utilization rates have remained in a band
between 83 per cent and 86 per cent.</p>
<p><em>Rig Locator</em> records show there were 673 rigs working across the
western provinces this week, with 119 rigs down (85 per cent utilization
rate).</p>
<p>Saskatchewan had the highest utilization rate of the four western provinces,
with 91 per cent of its fleet active this week (the same utilization rate as
last week). There were 106 active rigs in the province and 10 rigs were
down.</p>
<p>Alberta rig activity remained steady from last week with 84 per cent of the
fleet working. There are 491 rigs working in the province this week.</p>
<p>In British Columbia, 57 rigs are active for an 85 per cent utilization rate,
while in Manitoba there are 19 rigs working for 86 per cent utilization.</p>
<p>The most active operator this week is <strong>Husky Energy Inc.</strong>,
with 35 active rigs. <strong>Penn West Petroleum Ltd.</strong> nabbed second
place with 31 rigs at work across the basin.</p>
<p><strong>Canadian Natural Resources Limited</strong> has 25 active rigs, while
<strong>Cenovus Energy Inc.</strong> and <strong>ConocoPhillips Canada
Limited</strong> tied for fourth with 20 active rigs each.</p>
<p>Husky had 12 rigs drilling exploratory hole this week, the most of any
producer. <strong>Encana Corporation</strong> had nine rigs performing
exploratory work.</p>


